<help_entry>	<name>Read_chardata</name>	<succinct>Read a character matrix or set of character matrices</succinct>	<verbose>This function reads the character data contained in Phylip, Fasta, or 	Nexus formatted files. The function takes as input the path and name of a file 	(if the contents of only a single file is to be read) or the path to a directory 	(if all of the Phylip, Fasta, or Nexus files in a directory are to be read).</verbose>	<argument>		<arg_name>filename</arg_name>		<arg_description>A string that contains the path to a file in Phylip, Fasta,		or Nexus format.</arg_description>	</argument>	<argument>		<arg_name>directoryname</arg_name>		<arg_description>A string that contains the path to a directory that may contain many files in Phylip, Fasta,		or Nexus format.</arg_description>	</argument>		<usage>		<theory>read_chardata(filename)</theory>		<example>read_chardata(&quot;&frasl;users&frasl;jdoe&frasl;data&frasl;my_data.nex&quot;)</example>	</usage>	<usage>		<theory>read_chardata(directoryname)</theory>		<example>read_chardata(&quot;&frasl;users&frasl;jdoe&frasl;data&frasl;&quot;)</example>	</usage>	<author>John Huelsenbeck</author>	<reference>The Madisson^2 and Swofford paper.</reference></help_entry>